<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06129027 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06129027 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Kurtzig; PHOTO: Roberts  </CAPTION><LEADPARA>  LIGHTS! CAMERA! . . . Kurtzig?;    Could be. Sandra Kurtzig's newautobiography, &quot;CEO: Building a $400 Million Company from the Ground Up,&quot; hasbarely hit the book stores, and already the 44-year-old founder of MountainView-based Ask Computer Systems has received an inquiry about movie rights.Kurtzig, the only woman heading a large company in Silicon Valley, hasn'tdecided whether to accept the offer. But she has revealed her preference forthe actress to portray her: &quot;Pretty Woman&quot; star Julia Roberts.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HER LIFE MAY HIT THE SCREEN  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Bits andamp; BytesLee Gomes, Mike Langberg, Valerie Rice and Ron Wolf contributed to thiscolumn, which was compiled by Tom Schmitz.  </MEMO><TEXT>  (hbox);    HELLO, BRINKS?: Some people just can't wait to get their hands onSystem 7.0, the long-awaited overhaul of Apple's Macintosh operating systemsoftware, scheduled for introduction Monday.;    Chris Espinosa, who overseesmarketing of System 7.0 for Apple USA, was flying back from Boston last weekwith one of the first shrink-wrapped boxes of the new software. Apple hasdesigned an eye-catching package for retail display by its dealers -- apackage only a few people have seen. During the trip, he stowed the box underhis seat. Amid the usual confusion of disembarking after the plane landed inSan Francisco, a Mac aficionado apparently realized what the box held andstole it.; (hbox);    STILL WAITING: What's going on at Businessland? WallStreet analysts aren't sure, but they're starting to get worried.;    MostSilicon Valley companies that completed fiscal quarters on March 31 alreadyhave reported their earnings for the period. Not Businessland. The computerretailer originally planned to issue its financial report last week, then thisweek. Now the matter has been pushed into next week.;    Analysts fear thatBusinessland, which has lost money for five straight quarters, may bepreparing another unpleasant surprise. So far, Businessland has offered noexplanation. Calls to the company Tuesday were not returned.; (hbox);   FUTURECHIP: What will computer chips look like in the year 2000? Here's ahint: They'll have BIPS to die for.;    At the In-Stat conference in PhoenixTuesday, Craig Barrett, executive vice president of Intel, predicted that achip's calculating speed will be measured in how many billions of instructionsit can process in a second, not the measly millions boasted of today.Microprocessors will also control functions such as speech recognition andfull-motion video, all from an inch-square piece of silicon.;    To put thingsin perspective, Barrett told the audience Intel will introduce a RISC chipthis summer containing 2 million transistors. State-of-the-art microprocessorsnow have about 1.2 million.; (hbox);    MIS-DIRECTED: If computer-aideddriving is the next high-tech frontier, we're going to spend a lot of timelooking for the off-ramp.;    Perhaps you've seen those new computer doodadsthat let a user choose from a list of destinations, then prints out drivingdirections. Curious, a reporter asked the unit at the Santa Clara Marriott howto get to the San Jose Mercury News, but became perplexed when it told him totake Highway 101 north for about 40 miles to something called Market Street.Turns out the machine was correct, sort of. The directions led to the paper'stwo-person bureau in San Francisco.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910508  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  548  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday May 8, 199100129027,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyr